roger'`, the filter appends `TestExternalAgent`. But when triggered by `push` to `main` (no `inputs.agent`), roger-roger is included in the default agent list and the filter expression evaluates correctly. However, in `e2e-isolated.yml`, the test filter comes from `inputs.test`, not from the agent — there's no automatic `TestExternalAgent` filter for roger-roger in that workflow. Since roger-roger won't pass non-external-agent tests (e.g. the Vogon-style tests won't skip, they'll try to use roger-roger for generic prompts), this could cause spurious failures when someone manually triggers the isolated workflow with roger-roger and a broad test filter.\\n\\n**4. `ExternalAgent` interface could just be part of `Agent`**\\n\\nThe `ExternalAgent` interface has a single method `IsExternalAgent() bool`. Since it's optional and only checked via type assertions, this is fine. But consider whether a simpler approach (a method on `Agent` with a default `false`) would reduce the number of type assertions scattered around. Minor point — current approach is reasonable.\\n\\n**5. Consider `--no-gpg-sign` in test git commits**\\n\\n`external_agent_test.go` calls `s.Git(t, \\\"commit\\\", \\\"-m\\\", ...)`. The `Git` helper in `repo.go` doesn't add `--no-gpg-sign`. However, `SetupRepo` already configures user.name/email, and the CLAUDE.md notes that `testutil.InitRepo` disables GPG. The `SetupRepo` path doesn't explicitly disable GPG signing — if a CI runner has GPG signing enabled globally, these commits could fail. Worth checking whether `SetupRepo` already handles this (it uses `Git` which may inherit global config).\\n\\n**6. Minor: `roger_roger.go` uses `syscall.SysProcAttr{Setpgid: true}` — not portable**\\n\\nThis is darwin/linux only. Since E2E tests run on Linux CI, this is fine, but `//go:build !windows` might be worth adding for documentation if Windows support (PR #673) lands.\\n\\n### What looks good\\n\\n- Clean separation between agent adapter (`roger_roger.go`) and 